Abstract

The analysis examines user activity on the Base chain, particularly for the game “BlockLord,” using transaction volume and user engagement metrics. Additionally, it assesses “Rumble Racing Star” on Arbitrum for its user retention strategies and evaluates “Cat Tower,” a base game not using AA wallets, demonstrating consistent user activity with over 1,000 daily players. This comprehensive analysis aims to maximize return on effort by focusing on strategic game and chain deployment.

ChainSelection

There are more than 140 games currently on Base. With such a vast number of games on a single chain, achieving significant support from the off-take becomes challenging. Consequently, a more strategic focus is necessary.

Below is a bar chart displaying the number of games on each chain:

Topgame on ARB BLAST BASE

Blast has some games, but has not been doing well after the TGE, espcially considering Ultiverse has been doing poorly on it, this chain might not be kind to cross-chain new players. The best game, Cambria, was receiving BLAST gold for their players, whereas Crypto Valleys also received BLAST gold, but yet to perform. Given the Blast TGE has been terrible, this is not an ideal chain for new comers.

There are some games doing great numbers on ARB and BASE, both has great on-chain acitivities. While both have great UAW, BASE games, in general, have more on-chain transactions. At the sametime, BASE has a much more vibrant meme culture where some the total meme coins marketcap is at 1billion with over 270+million daily trading value. It is a much better chain for Gamefi deployment.

BlockLord User activity

In order to understand why certain games have gained popularity on Base, further analysis of on-chain user activities is essential. The following section demonstrates the on-chain user activity for “BlockLord” by tracking specific contract addresses:

  • x017405a2de0613e12cd3d7b67e691bfefc46debf - mission

  • 0x80625310Db240631A91f61659CCC550eA9761742 - duel

Blocklords and other Base top games are doing so many on-chain interaction because they are utlizing Account Abstraction (AA) wallets, allowing most in-game activities to be logged on-chain without much effort.

Here is a typical tx demonstrating how things are logged on-chain Here is how Blocklords active user, new user evolve over time. We identify those who completed daily quests, either mission or duel as active user.

Rumble Racing Star User activity

Rumble Racing Star User Activity Now, let’s examine the leading game on Arbitrum, “Rumble Racing Star.” The analysis focuses on key user engagement metrics:

  • Run 1 race on RRS
  • Hold and AP or MB NFT
  • Send Message on Telegram chat for Jambo

RRS does not use AA wallets, meaning all these wallets are active Web3 players, much better aligned with our goal.

Base game not using AA

Revisiting the base games that do not utilize AA wallets, such as “Cat Tower,” reveals consistent user activity. Although these games do not reach the transaction levels of the top games on ARB, they still maintain a solid user base, with over 1,000 daily players.

Conclusion This analysis aids in identifying promising games and chains for future deployment by focusing on user activity metrics and strategic benefits. By leveraging the data, decisions can be made to align with organizational goals and maximize potential return on effort.
